0w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*4KwtELNQQRbhJ3aBGg-kZg.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*4KwtELNQQRbhJ3aBGg-kZg.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*4KwtELNQQRbhJ3aBGg-kZg.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:822/1*4KwtELNQQRbhJ3aBGg-kZg.png 822w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:411/1*4KwtELNQQRbhJ3aBGg-kZg.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">A lot explanations I see on the subject of linear algebra tend to skip directly into topics such as inner products, matrices and vectors. I also see plenty of people veer into the subject’s applications to various different field such as big data, computer graphics and machine learning. I wanted to take a step back to explain where exactly the study of linear algebra comes from in detail and how someone could derive the subject themselves from scratch. This article won’t assume you know any mathematics past elementary algebra.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">As the name of the subject would leave you to guess linear algebra is related to linear equations, equations of the form <em>ax</em> + <em>by</em> = <em>c</em>. Which can be graphed as line.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:45%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 346px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:692/format:webp/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 692w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 346px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:692/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png 692w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:346/1*cwkW6DgJFUOtFTMv46IW7g.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">A common approach when analyzing a difficult problem is to play around with examples, so we will start by looking at a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_of_linear_equations" target="_self">system of linear equations</a></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">2<em>x</em> + 4<em>y</em> = 7 (1)</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>x</em> + 2<em>y</em> = 4 (2)</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">A common way to solve a system of equations like this is to use a technique known as <strong>elimination</strong>. We can go about this by multiplying our second equation <em>x</em> + 2<em>y</em> = 4 by 2. Which would give us</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">2<em>x</em> + 4<em>y</em> = 8</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">We can then subtract our first equation (1) by our second (2) which gives us</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">2<em>x</em> + 4<em>y</em>-(2<em>x</em> + 4<em>y</em>) = 8–7</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">0 = 1</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">There is clearly something wrong here, in fact this is what’s known as an <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_of_linear_equations#Consistency" target="_self">inconsistent</a> system of equation. In short this means our system of equations has no solution. We can continue playing around with our system by modifying the prior system of equations slightly giving us</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">2x + 4y = 8</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">x + 2y = 4</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If we take the same approach as prior using elimination to try to solve it we arrive with the following result</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">0 = 0</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Unlike the system prior which had no solution, this system has an infinite number of solutions. A system that has no solution or has an infinite number of solutions is known as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Underdetermined_system" target="_self">undetermined</a> and a system of linear equations with one solution is known as <strong>regular</strong>. At this point you should be scratching your head and theorizing that when trying to solve a system of linear equations we are left with three possible cases. We can have one possible solution, no solution or an infinite number of solutions. So now you might be wondering what exactly causes a system of linear equations to be regular or undetermined? To figure this out we will do what mathematicians typically attempt when trying to solve a problem we will come up with a generalization.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>ax</em> + <em>by</em> = <em>s</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>cx</em> + <em>dy</em> = <em>t</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">When looking back at the second system of linear equations that we studied we will notice a pattern. The first equation in each system can be transformed into the second by dividing each equation by two. This can lead us to assume that if an equation in our system is a multiple of another then the system is undetermined.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Using our generalized system of equations we will try to come up with a condition for our system having a solution. To do this we will once again apply the process of elimination. We will multiply our top equation <em>ax</em> +<em>by</em> = <em>s</em> by <em>d</em> and our bottom equation <em>cx</em> + <em>dy</em> = <em>t</em> by <em>b</em>. This will give us the following system of equations.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>adx</em> + <em>bdy</em> = <em>sd</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>bcx</em> + <em>bdy</em> = <em>bt</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Subtracting our top equation by the bottom one in our system gives us</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>adx</em>-<em>bcx</em> = <em>sd</em>-<em>bt</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">(<em>ad</em>-<em>bc</em>)<em>x</em> = <em>sd</em>-<em>bt</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now we just need to do what we do all the time in school. Solve for x!</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:46%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 353px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:706/format:webp/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 706w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 353px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:706/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png 706w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:353/1*vy1cmbUImst9YOtS9JALfQ.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">So we can find out what the value of <em>x</em> is in our system of equations as long as <em>ad</em>-<em>bc</em> is not 0.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">We now repeat the exact same process to eliminate <em>x</em> and solve for <em>y</em>, this time multiplying the top equation by <em>c</em> and bottom equation by <em>a</em>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>acx</em> + <em>bcy</em> = <em>sc</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>acx</em> + <em>ady</em> = <em>at</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Subtracting these gives us</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">(<em>ad</em>-<em>bc</em>)y=<em>at</em>-<em>sc</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
