750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*_J_D-PSSpsUWGok-I7aUIA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*_J_D-PSSpsUWGok-I7aUIA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*_J_D-PSSpsUWGok-I7aUIA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*_J_D-PSSpsUWGok-I7aUIA.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*_J_D-PSSpsUWGok-I7aUIA.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Solution set given two types of linear equations</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Next we can create a table for the values of ad-bc to check when it zero for a given pair of linear equations. For example when we have a oblique line, <em>ax</em>+<em>by</em>=<em>s</em>, we know that a and b are nonzero. If we take a horizontal line <em>cx</em> + <em>dy</em> = <em>t</em>. We know that <em>c</em> is 0, but <em>d</em> is nonzero. Using this we can reason what the value of <em>ad</em>-<em>bc</em> will be for this pair of equations We know that <em>d</em> must be 0 so <em>ad</em> is 0. We know both <em>b</em> and <em>c</em> are nonzero so we are left with</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">zero value — nonzero value = nonzero value</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Repeating this procedure for every given pair of possible lines we end up with another table.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*KdU4kr8Ja2uZRz3EAaQEfQ.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Values of ad-bc for any given pair of linear equations</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If you compare the past two tables you’ll see that when <em>ad</em>-<em>bc</em>=0 our set of solutions is just a single point.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">So given two linear equations we can now think about what the difference in their slopes would be. For the line <em>ax</em> + <em>by</em> = <em>s</em>, we have a slope of -<em>a</em>/<em>b</em> and for <em>cx</em> + <em>dy</em> = <em>t</em> we have a slope of -<em>c</em>/<em>d</em>. To find out when these slopes are the same we can take the difference giving us</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>a</em>/<em>b</em>- (-<em>c</em>/<em>d</em>)</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">= -<em>a</em>/<em>b</em>+<em>c</em>/<em>d</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">= — <em>ad</em>/<em>bd</em> + <em>bc</em>/<em>bd</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">=-(<em>ad</em>-<em>bc</em>)/<em>bd</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If <em>ad</em> — <em>bc</em> = 0 then the two lines in our system have the same slope, meaning they’re can’t be one solution. In the case of oblique lines we can have two parallel lines that don’t intersect in which case we have no solution, or we have the same line in which case there will be an infinite number of solutions. If the lines aIf <em>ad</em> — <em>bc</em> is not 0 then our two lines have different slopes resulting in a single solution, this is why we had a “?” in the cell for our oblique lines. Now we can see that given a system of two linear equations</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>ax</em> + <em>by</em> = <em>s</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>cx</em> + <em>dy</em> = <em>t</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">That we will have a unique solution if and only if <em>ad</em> — <em>bc</em> is not 0.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Final Remarks</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Thank you for taking the time to read through this! I plan to write more about Linear Algebra, specifically leading into the formal notion of a matrix.</p></div></div></div></section><?php include_once 'Elemental/footer.php'; ?>